      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. i think i remember my prof mentioning something about \"spooky action at a distance\" too. is that just another way of saying the same thing or is there a specific reason they call it spooky?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Spooky action at a distance\" is a term famously used by Albert Einstein to describe quantum entanglement. He found it \"spooky\" because it seemed to contradict his belief in local realism, the idea that objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings and that information cannot travel faster than the speed of light. In the case of entanglement, the \"spooky\" part comes from the fact that two entangled particles appear to instantly affect each other's state, no matter how far apart they are, seemingly defying the speed limit set by the speed of light. It's like two distant friends who can instantly share a thought, even though they are separated by a vast distance, which feels like magic to us. This phenomenon challenges our classical understanding of the world and has led to many debates and experiments in the field of quantum physics.",
      "source": "target",
